$\frac{\infty}{\infty}$ form. Apply L'H\^{o}pital's Rule three times:
\[
 \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{x^3}{e^x}
 = \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{3x^2}{e^x}
 = \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{6x}{e^x}
 = \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{6}{e^x}
 = 0.
\]
The exponential function $e^x$ eventually overwhelms *any* polynomial.
No matter how high the power of $x$, the exponential wins the race to
infinity.

$\frac{\infty}{\infty}$ form.
\[
 \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{\ln x}{\sqrt{x}}
 = \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{1/x}{1/(2\sqrt{x})}
 = \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{2\sqrt{x}}{x}
 = \limto{x \to \infty}\,\frac{2}{\sqrt{x}} = 0.
\]
Logarithms grow more slowly than *any* positive power of $x$.

